\section*{Section 3: Highest Common Factor and Lowest Common Multiple}

\begin{enumerate}
\item Find the \textbf{highest common factor (HCF)} of 84 and 156.

\item Find the HCF of 144, 180 and 240.

\item Find the \textbf{lowest common multiple (LCM)} of 48 and 180.

\item Find the LCM of 72, 90 and 150.

\item Find the HCF and LCM of the following, \textbf{leaving your answers in index form}:
\[
2^3 \times 3^2 \times 5,\qquad
2^2 \times 3^4 \times 7,\qquad
2^4 \times 3 \times 5^2.
\]

\item Given that $720 = 2^4 \times 3^2 \times 5$.
\begin{enumerate}
\item Express 504 as a product of prime factors (index form).
\item Hence, find the HCF and LCM of 720 and 504.
\end{enumerate}

\item The numbers 900 and 315, written as the product of prime factors, are
\[
900=2^2\times 3^2\times 5^2 \quad\text{and}\quad 315=3^2\times 5\times 7.
\]
Hence, find
\begin{enumerate}
\item the smallest integer $k$ such that $900k$ is a perfect cube,
\item the smallest integer $m$ such that $315m$ is a perfect square,
\item the largest integer which is a factor of both 900 and 315,
\item the smallest integer which is divisible by both 900 and 315.
\end{enumerate}

\item The numbers 450 and 672 are given.
\begin{enumerate}
\item Find their HCF and LCM.
\item Hence, find the smallest positive integer $n$ such that $450n$ is a multiple of 672.
\end{enumerate}

\item
\begin{enumerate}
\item Express 756 as a product of prime factors (index form).
\item Find the smallest positive integer $t$ such that $756t$ is a perfect square.
\item Find the smallest positive integer $u$ such that $756u$ is a perfect cube.
\end{enumerate}

\item Find the smallest positive integer $p$ such that $\sqrt{630p}$ is a whole number. Hence, find $\sqrt{630p}$.

\item Find the smallest positive integer $q$ such that $\dfrac{540}{q}$ is a perfect cube. (State $q$ and the cube.)

\item Find the smallest integers $x$ and $y$ such that $2^x \times 3^y \times 5^2$ is a multiple of 360.

\item Given that $588 = 2^2 \times 3 \times 7^2$ and $756 = 2^2 \times 3^3 \times 7$.
\begin{enumerate}
\item Find the HCF and LCM, leaving answers in index form.
\item Find the smallest positive integer $n$ such that $588n$ is a multiple of 756.
\end{enumerate}

\item The numbers 1260 and 840 are given.
\begin{enumerate}
\item Find the HCF and LCM.
\item Find the smallest positive integer $k$ such that $\dfrac{1260}{k}$ is a perfect square.
\item Find the smallest positive integer $m$ such that $840m$ is a perfect cube. (Leave $m$ in prime factors.)
\end{enumerate}

\item Let $N = 2^3 \times 3 \times 5^2 \times 7^3$.
Find the smallest positive integer $k$ such that $Nk$ is \textbf{both} a perfect square and a perfect cube. (Leave $k$ in index form.)
\end{enumerate}

\section*{Section 4: HCF--LCM Word Problems}

\begin{enumerate}
\item 132 boys and 210 girls signed up for a camp. They are to be divided into mixed groups such that the number of boys in each group is the same and the number of girls in each group is the same.
\begin{enumerate}
\item Find the largest possible number of groups.
\item Hence, find the number of boys in each group.
\item Hence, find the number of girls in each group.
\end{enumerate}

\item A company packs 864 boxes of snacks, 1056 bottles of water and 720 sandwiches into as many goodie bags as possible. Each goodie bag must have the same contents.
\begin{enumerate}
\item What is the maximum number of goodie bags that can be prepared?
\item How many of each item are in each goodie bag?
\end{enumerate}

\item Three traffic lights will turn red at fixed intervals of 50 s, 1 min 20 s, and 1 min 35 s respectively. They all turn red simultaneously at 09 15 00. Find the next time when they will turn red simultaneously again.

\item Three school bells ring at fixed intervals of 1 min 12 s, 1 min 30 s, and 1 min 48 s respectively. They ring together at 14 12. Find the next time they will ring together again.

\item Three comets pass through our solar system every 60 years, 84 years and 210 years respectively. They were last seen together in the year 1900. In which year will they be seen together again?

\item The floor of a hall is 4.8 m by 7.5 m and is to be laid with identical square tiles.
\begin{enumerate}
\item Find the largest possible side length (in cm) of each tile.
\item Find the number of tiles needed.
\end{enumerate}

\item A contractor has ropes of lengths 3.6 m, 4.2 m and 5.4 m. He wants to cut them into equal pieces of the greatest possible length, with no leftover.
\begin{enumerate}
\item Find the length of each piece in cm.
\item Find how many pieces can be cut from each rope.
\end{enumerate}

\item Three toy cars $A,B,C$ start at the same point on a circular track. They take 96 s, 120 s, and 150 s respectively to complete one round. The race starts at 09 50.
\begin{enumerate}
\item At what time will they next meet at the start point again?
\item How many rounds has car $A$ completed by then?
\end{enumerate}

\item Three buses arrive at a bus stop every 18 min, 24 min, and 45 min respectively. They arrive together at 08 20. Find the next time they will arrive together again.

\item A bakery has some tarts. There are always 5 tarts left over whether the tarts are packed into boxes of 6, 8 or 15. What is the minimum possible number of tarts?

\item A ribbon is shared equally among 5 tailors. One tailor cuts his share into 6 cm pieces, another into 9 cm pieces, another into 15 cm pieces, another into 18 cm pieces, and the last into 24 cm pieces. To avoid wastage, each tailor must have no leftover after cutting. Find the least possible total length of the original ribbon (in cm).

\item Cylindrical cans $A,B,C$ (same radii) have heights 12 cm, 18 cm, and 20 cm respectively. They are stacked (using only one type per stack) to reach the same height.
\begin{enumerate}
\item Find the minimum common height.
\item Find the minimum number of $B$ cans required.
\end{enumerate}

\item Boxes $P,Q,R$ have heights 9 cm, 14 cm, and 21 cm respectively. They are stacked to form towers of equal height.
\begin{enumerate}
\item Find the minimum height of each tower.
\item Find the minimum number of $Q$ boxes needed.
\end{enumerate}

\item Three robot arms repeat a cycle every 12 s, 18 s, and 30 s respectively. They begin a cycle together at 16 05 30.
\begin{enumerate}
\item When will they next begin a cycle together?
\item How many cycles will the 12 s arm complete by that time?
\end{enumerate}

\item A charity wants to pack 168 bottles, 252 food packs and 420 masks into as many identical care packs as possible, with none left over.
\begin{enumerate}
\item Find the maximum number of care packs.
\item State the contents of each care pack.
\end{enumerate}
\end{enumerate}

